Here's how to save and restore draft text using Window lifecycle events:

**1. Create a custom `Window` subclass in `App.xaml.cs`:**

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    {
        var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

        window.Stopped += (s, e) =>
        {
            // Save draft when app goes to background
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", NotesViewModel.Instance.DraftText);
        };

        window.Resumed += (s, e) =>
        {
            // Restore draft when app returns
            NotesViewModel.Instance.DraftText =
                Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
        };

        window.Destroying += (s, e) =>
        {
            // Android back-button can skip Stopped entirely
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", NotesViewModel.Instance.DraftText);
        };

        return window;
    }
}
```

**2. Or use a `Window` subclass for cleaner separation:**

```csharp
public class AppWindow : Window
{
    private readonly NotePageViewModel _vm;

    public AppWindow(Page page, NotePageViewModel vm) : base(page)
    {
        _vm = vm;
    }

    protected override void OnStopped()
    {
        base.OnStopped();
        Preferences.Set("draft_text", _vm.DraftText);
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        _vm.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }

    protected override void OnDestroying()
    {
        base.OnDestroying();
        Preferences.Set("draft_text", _vm.DraftText);
    }
}
```

Then in `App.xaml.cs`:

```csharp
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    => new AppWindow(new AppShell(), myViewModel);
```

**Key things to know:**

| Concern | Guidance |
|---|---|
| **Why `Stopped` not `Deactivated`?** | `Deactivated` fires for dialogs/split-screen — the app may not actually background |
| **Why also `Destroying`?** | On Android, the back button can skip `Stopped` and go straight to `Destroying` |
| **Why `Preferences`?** | It's fast and synchronous — lifecycle handlers must complete in 1–2 seconds to avoid ANR/watchdog kills |
| **`Resumed` vs first launch** | `Resumed` does **not** fire on first launch (sequence is `Created → Activated`), so load initial state in your viewmodel constructor |

`Preferences` is ideal for small text. For larger drafts, use `File.WriteAllText` to a known path instead.
